The Enclosed runner treats all static nested classes as test classes. If any static nested classes have no methods annotated with `@Test` you will get a failure. This prevents you from having a nested class that is a helper class. It would be great if Enclosed would ignore those classes.

Suggestion: Make Enclosed runner ignore all the inner classes annotated with @Ignore just like it works for ignoring the tests with @Ignore.

    @RunWith(Enclosed.class)
    public class RootTest {
	
      @Ignore
      public static class B {
        ......
      }
	
      public static class FooTest {
        @Test
        public void testFoo() {
          B b = new B();
          ....
        }
      }
    }

When using JUnit with an embedded CDI container... it is very helpful to have StackTrace information written to the console when the CDI container fails to launch.

Accordingly, we have hacked the protected final runLeaf(Statement statement, Description description, RunNotifier notifier) method to include conditional printing of the stack trace:

	/**
	 * Runs a {@link Statement} that represents a leaf (aka atomic) test.
	 * 
	 * @param statement
	 * @param description
	 * @param notifier
	 */
	protected final void runLeafSOAj(final Statement statement,
			final Description description, final RunNotifier notifier) {
		final EachTestNotifier eachNotifier = new EachTestNotifier(notifier,
				description);
		eachNotifier.fireTestStarted();
		try {
			statement.evaluate();
		} catch (final AssumptionViolatedException e) {
			eachNotifier.addFailedAssumption(e);
		} catch (final Throwable e) {

			// *******************************************
			// * Conditional print of stack trace added. *
			// *******************************************

			if (!(e instanceof AssertionError)) {
				e.printStackTrace();
			}

			eachNotifier.addFailure(e);
		} finally {
			eachNotifier.fireTestFinished();
		}
	}

having Assert.fail() (and Assert.fail(String message)) return AssertionError as their type would be useful in certain (admittedly rare) cases where a unit test calls a method with a non-void return type that has a fail() call at the end of the method (for example, iterating over a collection looking for a particular element to return, and if the loop is exited it wasn't and you want to trigger a junit failure.)

In the case above the code:
    fail();
    return null;

could be replaced with a single line:
    throw fail();

and the compiler would be happy.

this is identical to the return type pattern used by Guava in Throwables: http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/base/Throwables.html#propagate(java.lang.Throwable) and while it is a niche case where this would be useful, it would not (as far as I know) impact any backwards compatibility or surface in any way when users did not want it to.

I have noticed that when we changed a few tests of ours to use the Parameterized runner, the @Category annotation stops working; ie our performance test suite skips tests like the one attached below.

We are using gradle and junit 4.11 in the project.

I tried to rectify the problem by removing the overridden method getRunnerAnnotations() in Parameterized.TestClassRunnerForParameters and it solves my problem. I'm not sure what other problems this would introduce, though...

Best regards 
/ Per

```
import org.junit.Test;
import org.junit.experimental.categories.Category;
import org.junit.runner.RunWith;
import org.junit.runners.Parameterized;

import static java.util.Collections.singletonList;

@Category(PerformanceTest.class)
@RunWith(Parameterized.class)
public class TheMissingPerformanceTest
{
    @Parameterized.Parameters
    public static Iterable<Object[]> data()
    {
        return singletonList(new Object[0]);
    }

    @Test
    public void testSomething() throws Exception
    {
    }
}
